3. solae plural because the top hops from one spot to another as the whip is applied. It occupies more than one solum, cp. rivos, r, 1, 28, Catull. 63, 7, ‘etiam recente terrae sola sanguine maculans'; id. 40, ‘lustravit aethera album, sola dura, mare serum,’ etc-turben: the old nom. turben here is voucbed sor by Charisius (145, 8 K). See Neue-Wagener, 1, p. 258.

4. ab arte: one would expect the simple ablative ol manner. This is the first appearance of it in poetry, where, as bere, it is rarely without an attributive.
